title: Could my dentist have closed a tooth with an open nerve?
self_text: Two weeks ago I went to the dentist. He had to fix and close a cavity. I was told that the operation was very urgent because the cavities were deep and I would have risked devitalizing the tooth.  The problem is that I think the dentist, while removing the cavities, went too deep and under covered/hit the nerve of the tooth. While operating I could feel that feeling of "nakedness" and pain, but I was not sure it was my nerve discovered. But the dentist didn’t say anything and proceeded to close my tooth. I have had an infernal pain in my tooth for two weeks now, it’s the same feeling as a dental abscess but without any noticeable swelling. I suppose the reason is the one I just described, but I don’t know if I’m right, or the dentist did everything in order and the pain is caused by some other problem of mine.  Now, I wanted to know if it is possible that a dentist could have made such a mistake without realizing it, what would be the consequences of such an action and what should I do to fix it?  ​  16, AFAB, no smoke, no alchol, 5'5, around 155 pounds, don't take any particular medication

title: Am I the only one who finds the McDonalds UK adverts annoying?
self_text: I find the overly-familiar, somewhat working class  "Jack the lad"/"cheeky chappy" tone of the voice actor really quite irritating, in terms of I instantly change the radio or TV station when he comes on.  In a way I think it's a bit presumptuous about the demographic/mentality of the typical McDonalds customer so quite condescending actually. They're clearly targeting the "chav"/working class male demographic in my opinion, for lack of a better term.  The voice has grated on me for years, but I've only just really analysed why. They've kept the same voice actor for years and years so they must think his schtick works, but for me it just reinforces my perception of McDonalds being a really down market place.
